It all depends on what you need to implement and what the transaction flow is.

As an example, in one instance we needed to display some information alongside CRM data, so we created a Web Resource with some Javscript code which invoked a plugin, which in itself called the web service and returned a JSON. Then used **KnockOut.js** to render it into the Web Resource.

In other instance we are developing a plugin which waits for some state on a Lead, validates information and if all is Ok invokes a Web Service to create the account in some other application. If that application is successful, then the plugin Qualifies the Lead and the flow continues in CRM.

If you need the Web Service invocation as part of the data for a transaction, you would probably want to have a plugin with an action to use in a workflow, or listen for some message on an entity to retrieve/validate/invoke your Web Service.

If you just need to display some information, you can create a Web Resource and it&#39;ll be simpler.

Some resources I found useful are:&lt;br&gt;
 - [Tutorial: Write and register a plug-in][1]&lt;br&gt;
 - [Creating Custom Actions for Dynamics 365 with C#][2]&lt;br&gt;
 - [How to Trigger Plugins on Custom Messages using Actions in Dynamics 365][3]&lt;br&gt;

  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powerapps/developer/common-data-service/tutorial-write-plug-in
  [2]: https://www.ashishvishwakarma.com/Writing-Custom-Actions-C-Sharp-Code-Dynamics-365/
  [3]: https://www.magnetismsolutions.com/blog/dominicjarvis/2017/09/18/how-to-trigger-plugins-on-custom-messages-using-actions-in-dynamics-365

typesafe-actions has a helper type called [ActionType][1], which will do that union for you if you have a map object of the actions. The easiest way to do this is in another file, with an `import *`. For example:

```
import { ActionType } from &#39;typesafe-actions&#39;
import * as counterActions from &#39;insert/filepath/here&#39;

export type CounterActions = ActionType&lt;typeof counterActions&gt;;
```

In my application, we do this in a file for the RootAction, which just or&#39;s together all the actions we create throughout the app. So the file looks like:

```
import * as fooActions from &#39;./foo/actions&#39;
import * as barActions from &#39;./bar/actions&#39;
// etc

export type RootAction = 
  ActionType&lt;typeof fooActions&gt;
  | ActionType&lt;typeof barActions&gt;
  // etc
```

  [1]: https://github.com/piotrwitek/typesafe-actions#actiontype

